Author: scifichick774<br>
Rating: PG<br>
Category: Drama  W/S friendship w/really minor UST hinting <br>
Spoilers: Anything up to and including ‘Lady Heather’s Box’<br>
Summary: Warrick and Sara talk about certain relationships.  Those of you who are fond of Hank should not read this.<br>
Disclaimer: Not mine, no infringement intended, please don’t sue.<br>
Feedback: I would love feedback.<br>
Archival: Sure – just let me know where.<br>
Author’s Note: My CSI muse has been dead and buried for a long time, so this fic is more for Melindotty than anyone else because she requested it.  It’s all angsty fluff, so don’t go looking for a plot that isn’t there (in other words, all the case stuff is filler).  Hope you like it. <br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
“Sindee Campbell.  S-i-n-d-e-e,” Warrick said as he and Sara rode the elevator to the victim’s tenth story apartment.  “You think that was her real name?”  Sara grinned at the joking quality in his voice.<br>
<br>
“Could be.  You can never tell these days,” she answered.  Warrick gave a partial roll of his eyes and shook his head lightly.  “Warrick is *your* real name, and it’s not common,” she pointed out.<br>
<br>
“It’s a family name,” he said.  Sara smiled.<br>
<br>
“Well, Vegas is Sin City; maybe her name is some sort of tribute,” she only half-joked.  Sindee’s apartment wasn’t far from the elevators and the second Sara saw the living room through the open door, she smiled brightly at Warrick.  “Or not.”<br>
<br>
The police officers watched them slip on their synthetic latex gloves and then stepped aside as Sara and Warrick entered the apartment.  Brass gave a nod of his head to acknowledge their presence and they walked over to him; Sara carrying a collection kit and the camera dangling from Warrick’s neck.  Brass looked tired and gave Sara a warning look when he saw the teasing grin on her lips.<br>
<br>
“Don’t start,” he said.  The apartment, or at least the living room, was decked out much like a club.  The multi-colored lighting was spinning and pulsating, and Sara was certain they could find a button for the strobe light with a little effort.  The living room had a pole in the middle of the room and what little furniture there was seemed to be angled around it.  <br>
<br>
“Dancer?”  Warrick asked, guessing the woman’s occupation.  <br>
<br>
“Accountant,” Brass answered.  Warrick looked surprised and Sara just smiled as she got her collection kit ready.<br>
<br>
“Too bad.  If she was a dancer then she could have written all this stuff off,” she said.  Brass snickered.  Warrick frowned when he held the camera up to his eye.<br>
<br>
“Is there any other lighting in here besides *that*?”<br>
<br>
“You wish,” Brass said.  “You can open the curtains or I can request some standing lights be brought in.”  Warrick nodded.<br>
<br>
“Do that.  We don’t want to disrupt the scene by opening the curtains.”<br>
<br>
Brass nodded and left with the officers while Sara started collecting what evidence she could see that didn’t need pictures taken of it first.  Warrick looked around and pointed out the things that caught his eye, but he couldn’t take any pictures until the lighting was sent over.  Sara, despite the environment, was in ‘the zone’ and not talking much unless it was to herself about something she found.  Warrick was bored and decided to start up a conversation.  If nothing else, he figured he could tease Sara as subtly as he could about her relationship with Hank.<br>
<br>
“How’s Hank?”  He asked casually.  Sara didn’t even turn to look at him when she answered.<br>
<br>
“Fine as far as I know,” she said.  Warrick arched an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“As far as you know?”<br>
<br>
“What does this look like to you?”  She asked, bypassing his question by pointing at the still wet stain on the floor.  He narrowed his eyes as he crouched down to look at it.<br>
<br>
“It’s not blood.  It doesn’t look thick enough to be paint.  You get a sample?”<br>
<br>
“Yeah,” she said and flashed him a quick smile.  “I’m just impatient.”  He nodded knowingly and stood up.  Warrick took a few steps around the area and Sara smiled at him again as she placed a swab into a collection bag.  “You’re bored.”<br>
<br>
“Yeah,” he acknowledged.  “What kind of person has club lighting as regular lighting for their apartment?”<br>
<br>
“I don’t know,” she said.  “Maybe she just couldn’t get enough of the scene?  Didn’t you tell me that it can be addictive?”<br>
<br>
“Sometimes,” he answered with a shrug.  “But it can also get really old really fast.”  She grinned at him.<br>
<br>
“Don’t tell me they won’t be expecting you at Venus this weekend?”  Sara asked in mock surprise.  Warrick grinned.<br>
<br>
“I’m working this weekend,” he said.  “But I could leave a message with the bouncer if *you* want to go.”  Sara snorted at the absurd teasing comment.<br>
<br>
“Not my thing, remember?”  She started to label something, but looked up at him briefly.  “And I’m a little hurt that you don’t think I could get in by myself,” she joked.<br>
<br>
“You could,” Warrick responded and then leaned his head to the side and gave her a measured look.  “But Hank couldn’t.”  Sara finished what she was doing and looked directly in his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Greg told you,” she said in an observational tone.  She shook her head and started to look around the room.  “I knew I shouldn’t have told him.”  Warrick allowed himself to frown, but only because Sara’s eyes weren’t focused on him.  Greg knew something he didn’t?<br>
<br>
“Yeah, because Greg and I are always having those deep, meaningful conversations,” he said sarcastically.  Sara chuckled and swept some hair behind her ear.  “What happened?”  He asked seriously.<br>
<br>
“We broke up,” Sara admitted.  <br>
<br>
“Sorry.  I didn’t know.”<br>
<br>
“It’s okay, no big deal,” she said.<br>
<br>
“Ouch.”<br>
<br>
“It wasn’t like that,” Sara argued.  “You know how it is.  You date someone from work, but you barely get to see each other *because* of work.  We’re still friends.”<br>
<br>
“Okay.”  His tone indicated that he didn’t believe her and Sara shot him a forced grin.  “But you didn’t actually work with him, so you can’t use that as an excuse.”<br>
<br>
“Yes I ---”<br>
<br>
“If you had worked *with* him, then he would be a CSI.  And no offense, but he’s not that smart.”  He watched her mouth open slightly to speak, but he cut her off.  “Which I’m guessing is the real reason you dumped him.”  Sara was silent for a second while she considered her response.  Warrick could be entirely too insightful for his own good.  <br>
<br>
“What makes you think I dumped him?”  She finally asked.  One corner of Warrick’s mouth curled upward.<br>
<br>
“Well, he wasn’t going to dump you,” he pointed out.  There was another pause.  “No comeback?”  Sara’s lips curled into a smile.<br>
<br>
“I was going to ask why you’re suddenly so interested in my personal life, but then it struck me.  You’ve been hanging out with Nick too much,” she finally said.  A strange expression crossed Warrick’s face and he nodded.<br>
<br>
“I think you might have a point,” he said somewhat begrudgingly.  After pausing for a minute he looked serious again.  “Another man?”<br>
<br>
“What?”  Sara had gone back to trying to scan the apartment with her eyes, and was taken a little off guard by Warrick’s question.  He shrugged.<br>
<br>
“You two seemed to be getting along okay, and if you didn’t dump him then ---”<br>
<br>
“I wasn’t cheating on him, Warrick.  Sometimes things just don’t work out.”<br>
<br>
“Another woman?”  He asked.  Sara laughed.<br>
<br>
“I’m straight.”<br>
<br>
“That’s not what I meant.”<br>
<br>
“I know what you meant,” she said.  Their eyes caught each other and they stared at each other silently until a voice came bellowing into the apartment from the doorway.<br>
<br>
“Let there be light.”  Brass’s voice snapped them out of their thoughts and both turned to look at him.  A couple of the officers helped to set up the lighting and then Brass turned off the club lighting in the apartment.  <br>
<br>
“Thanks Brass,” Sara said.  “I was starting to get a headache.”<br>
<br>
“No problem.  You need a ride back?”<br>
<br>
“I’m gonna take a look around again now that we have good lighting.  See if there’s anything I missed,” she said.  Brass nodded and gave a small wave of his hand.<br>
<br>
“Later.”<br>
<br>
Brass left and Warrick started placing number cards down and taking pictures for evidence.  At the same time, Sara began looking around for any additional evidence that she may have missed.  The next twenty minutes went by without them saying anything to each other.<br>
<br>
“Done?”  Warrick finally asked.  Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
“I think that’s all I’m going to get for now.  Good thing Brass brought the lights over though.  I would have missed a few hairs and fiber samples,” she said.  Warrick nodded absently as his eyes fixed on the tape outlining where the victim’s body had been.<br>
<br>
“Accountant,” he muttered under his breath.<br>
<br>
“You never can tell,” Sara said.  Their eyes caught each other’s again and after a while, Warrick nodded once in agreement.<br>
<br>
“No, you never can.”<br>
<br>
<br>
