<br>
~*~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Warrick spotted Sara peering into a microscope and quietly entered the lab.  It almost seemed like she had been avoiding him, but Warrick knew better than to take it personally.  She was the kind of woman who lived for her job – and that was part of the problem.<br>
<br>
He walked up right next to her before she even noticed him.  Sara glanced at him through the corner of her eye and then grinned.<br>
<br>
“Hey,” she greeted.<br>
<br>
“Hey,” he said.  Sara didn’t elaborate on whatever it was that she was working on like she usually did, so Warrick took the opening he was given.  “You lied to me.”  Sara looked up at him with a confused expression on her face.<br>
<br>
“When did I do that?”<br>
<br>
“You said you and Hank didn’t break up because of another woman.”<br>
<br>
“No, I didn’t,” she said with a slight twinkle in her eye, only dulled because of the topic they were discussing.  “I said that we didn’t break up because of another man.  When you asked me about another woman, I dodged the question.”  She stopped talking and tilted her head to the side.  “How did you find out about that anyway?”  Warrick gave her a small grin and she rolled her eyes.  “God, Catherine has a big mouth.”  She went back to looking at the samples under the microscope and didn’t notice that Warrick leaned his back against the counter.<br>
<br>
“Apparently so do you after you’ve had a few drinks,” he said.  Sara didn’t look up at him this time.<br>
<br>
“I don’t suppose we could *not* talk about this?”<br>
<br>
“Sure,” Warrick said with a shrug of his shoulders.  “But what was with all that female bonding stuff?  I would have taken you out for a beer if you told me about it.”<br>
<br>
Sara laughed.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, but you would’ve taken me to one of those nightclubs on the strip.”<br>
<br>
“Where’d Catherine take you?”<br>
<br>
“Little bar over on Sahara,” she answered.<br>
<br>
“Nice?”<br>
<br>
“It served its purpose,” Sara stated with a wry grin.<br>
<br>
“The purpose being to get you drunk,” Warrick said in an observational tone.<br>
<br>
“Yep.”<br>
<br>
Warrick folded his arms across his chest and shook his head slightly.  Hank had really done a job on Sara and it might be a while before she even considered getting away from her semi-antisocial tendencies again.  <br>
<br>
“You talk to anyone while you were there?”  Warrick asked, already knowing what the answer would be.<br>
<br>
“Catherine.”<br>
<br>
“Besides Catherine?”  He asked.  Sara opened her mouth to speak, but Warrick cut her off.  “Or the bartender.”<br>
<br>
“Not that I recall.”<br>
<br>
“Ah.  So it was one of *those* drunk nights.”<br>
<br>
Sara turned to Warrick with an exasperated look on her face.<br>
<br>
“What’s with you today?”<br>
<br>
“What do you mean?”<br>
<br>
“At the scene, you were asking me a bunch of personal questions, but I thought that was because you were bored.  And now, you’re ---”<br>
<br>
“I’m just trying to be your friend, Sara.  It’s not healthy to make your life all about the job.”<br>
<br>
Sara sighed and closed her eyes for a second.  <br>
<br>
“I thought you’d been hanging around Nick, but apparently you’ve been hanging around Grissom,” she mumbled under her breath and then turned to sort through some samples.  Warrick looked at her quizzically.  “He said the same thing a couple of years ago,” she explained.  Warrick raised his eyebrows thoughtfully and then gave her a pointed look.  Sara forced a tight grin onto her lips.  “Look, I’m fine.  *Really*.  Okay?”  Warrick got a determined look on his face and Sara barely held back a cringe.  “What?”<br>
<br>
“You’re going out with me tonight.”<br>
<br>
“Excuse me?”<br>
<br>
“You heard me,” Warrick said.  “I’ll take you to that dive on Sahara if you want, but I don’t want you to go back to the way you were.”  Sara arched an eyebrow at him.<br>
<br>
“And how was I?”<br>
<br>
“Completely anti-social,” he said without any hesitation.  “The people here care about you, Sara.”  Sara looked at him skeptically and he tilted his head to the side.  “And I’ll catch hell from Catherine if you crawl back under your rock again.”<br>
<br>
“Nice,” she said sarcastically.  Warrick grinned.  <br>
<br>
“So, are you goin’ or what?”<br>
<br>
“It didn’t sound like you were giving me a choice,” she said observantly.<br>
<br>
“Good point,” Warrick agreed, pushing himself away from the counter.  “We can leave after work.”  He started to walk toward the door when Catherine appeared in the doorway.<br>
<br>
“You can leave after work for *where*?” she asked curiously, and if Sara didn’t know any better, then she would say almost *teasingly*.  Sara flashed a smile at Catherine.<br>
<br>
“Warrick wants to have a girl’s night out,” she said cheekily.  Catherine arched an eyebrow at him and Warrick rolled his eyes.<br>
<br>
“I told her I was taking her out,” he tried to explain to Catherine.  Catherine’s lips curled into a Cheshire-like smile.<br>
<br>
“Like on a date?” she teased, stealing a glance past Warrick at Sara.<br>
<br>
“No,” Sara replied.  “And I wouldn’t even be going if you hadn’t told him about Hank.”  Catherine shrugged unrepentantly and looked at Warrick.<br>
<br>
“Oh.  Well, glad I told you then,” she said, giving him another smile.  Sara pursed her lips and went back to looking through the microscope.  “So, as long as this is just a ‘friends’ thing, do you mind if I come?”  Warrick shot her a look which Catherine had to try desperately hard not to laugh at.<br>
<br>
“Sure – whatever,” Sara answered, not looking up at the two of them.  Catherine’s smile was beaming and her eyes were fixed on a somewhat upset looking Warrick.<br>
<br>
“Oh, wait.  I forgot.  My sitter is out of town,” she said, the smile still plastered on her face.  Warrick gave her a tight grin.<br>
<br>
“Maybe next time,” Sara said, still not looking up from the specimen.  <br>
<br>
“Yeah!  That’d be great,” Catherine said.  She turned to walk out back into the hallway when she stopped herself.  “Oh, yeah!  Grissom wants us all in his office in ten – or at least it was ten a few minutes ago.”  She mumbled the last part to herself and walked away without another word.  <br>
<br>
Warrick leaned against the door frame and waited for what Catherine said to sink into Sara’s brain.  Sara raised her head and was seemingly staring at the wall in front of her.<br>
<br>
“Did she just say we’re supposed to be in Grissom’s office?”<br>
<br>
“Yup.”<br>
<br>
“Oh.”  Sara started putting away the samples and specimens and was surprised to see that Warrick was still waiting for her when she finished.  She smiled at him as they walked out of the lab.  “Why didn’t you just go ahead?  You could have told them I would be late.”<br>
<br>
“Yeah, right,” Warrick said, unconvinced.  “If I told them that, then they’d think you were never coming.”<br>
<br>
“I am *not* that bad,” she protested.<br>
<br>
“Yes you are,” he said with a light grin.  Sara smiled and shook her head.<br>
<br>
This was going to be an interesting night.<br>
