<br>
Warrick and Sara walked into Grissom’s office, the other CSI staff turning around to look at them as they came in.  Grissom briefly glanced at them, giving them a nod of acknowledgement along with a somewhat disapproving look for their two minute tardiness, but quickly turned his attention back to the folders on his desk.  <br>
<br>
“Ok-ay,” he started, stringing out his word as he looked back and forth between a couple of folders.  Making a decision, he held one out to Catherine as he spoke.  “You and Nick get the Jane Doe who washed up in the Lake Mead Rec Area.  The call-in said her head and hands were cut off, so we need to do everything we can to identify the body.”  Catherine’s eyebrows rose as an unspoken question.  When Grissom chose to ignore it, Nick spoke up.<br>
<br>
“Are we gonna have to call in the feds?”<br>
<br>
Grissom gave him an expression that lay somewhere between a blank stare and a cutting look.  <br>
<br>
“Not if you do your job,” he answered, raising his voice at the end as a hint that Nick and Catherine should be on their way.  <br>
<br>
Catherine barely resisted the urge to snicker as they made their way out of the office.  Warrick and Sara watched them leave and when Sara turned back around to face Grissom, she had a smile on her face.<br>
<br>
“So – Nick and Catherine get a db – what do we get?” she asked.  Warrick’s eyes fell to the floor as he shook his head a little in disbelief.  She lived for the job - that much was obvious; the question was how he could get her to live her life without her job being the central focus.<br>
<br>
“A night off actually,” Grissom answered without looking up from the other folder on his desk.  Sara looked like she had just been punched in the gut.  She stood there staring at him, blinking a couple of times as if she expected what he had said to change.<br>
<br>
“What?”<br>
<br>
Grissom finally looked up and gave her a small grin.<br>
<br>
“I know you’re unfamiliar with the concept, but you and Warrick get a night off.  Brass just let me know that the boyfriend confessed on the Campbell case you two were working on and I’m taking Greg on the Rick Everson case ---”<br>
<br>
“You’re taking *Greg*?” Sara interrupted, the shock and hurt coming through in her voice.  “But ---” <br>
<br>
Grissom sighed and placed his hands down on his desk as he looked straight into Sara’s eyes.<br>
<br>
“He needs field experience, Sara, and the Everson case looks like a nice easy one to get him started on.”<br>
<br>
“Easy?” Sara scoffed.  “I thought you said we should never assume anything?”<br>
<br>
“I said it *looks like* an easy case, not that it would be,” Grissom countered and then turned his attention back to getting his things together.  “Besides, Catherine said that you had a night out planned.”<br>
<br>
“Nothing that we couldn’t cancel,” Sara protested.  Grissom stared at her for a second.<br>
<br>
“We?” he asked.  <br>
<br>
“Wa---”<br>
<br>
Grissom quickly shook his head and grabbed his keys, choosing not to dwell on her choice of wording any longer than he needed to.  He placed his hand on her shoulder as he came around the desk and gave her a stubborn expression.  <br>
<br>
“The point is that it’s nothing that you *need* to cancel,” he said, cutting off what she was about to say.  “Life is a system of checks and balances and you can’t let one area of your life take over the others.”  Sara lifted one eyebrow into the air, silently mocking him, and Grissom gave her a tight grin.  “Unless you’re me.”  He nodded his head at Warrick as a goodbye and motioned for them to leave the room so he could lock the door behind him.<br>
<br>
Sara watched him leave, collecting an already waiting and somewhat hyperactive-looking Greg along the way.<br>
<br>
“Ever feel like you’re being ganged up on?” she asked, not turning around to look at Warrick as she spoke.<br>
<br>
“Only when I am.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
“No offense, Sara, but ---”<br>
<br>
“I know, I know,” Sara interrupted and then took a swig from the bottle of beer in front of her, “I have bad taste in men.”<br>
<br>
Warrick tilted his head to the side and a bemused grin overtook his lips.<br>
<br>
“Sounds like you’ve heard that before,” he observed.<br>
<br>
“Several times,” she confirmed.  “But you know, maybe that’s the way it’s supposed to be.”<br>
<br>
Warrick raised an eyebrow before taking a drink of his own beer.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean?”  <br>
<br>
He knew it was a dangerous topic to get into, but he figured it was worth a shot given that their entire conversation since they had gotten to the bar an hour and a half ago had been teetering on the edge of appropriate for what kind of friends they were.   Friends, but there was always the hint of a possibility of something more; the awkward pauses when they would just be looking at each other, the not-so-subtle friendly flirting they did when they worked together; it was enough to make Warrick wonder whether he really wanted to hear Sara’s answer to the question he just asked.<br>
<br>
Sara leaned closer to him in an attempt to talk over the loud country music pouring out of the jukebox.  <br>
<br>
“Well, not everyone can have a boyfriend who buys them three hundred dollar purses, now can they?” she asked wryly, the corners of her lips curling upward into an almost teasing grin.  “Maybe, because of the kind of person I am, the job I do, maybe short and only partial relationships are the best I’m going to be able to do.  Can you really see me with the white picket fence, 3.2 kids, and ---” she trailed off when she saw the serious look on his face, like he was boring into her soul with his eyes.  “What?”<br>
<br>
He paused for a second before answering, shifting the intense look on his face into something a little more lighthearted, hoping that he had done it in time for her not to be too suspicious of what he had been thinking.<br>
<br>
“That always bothered me,” he finally said.  “How can someone have twenty percent of a kid?”  Sara beamed him an impish smile.<br>
<br>
“Joint custody?” she teasingly suggested, tilting back her bottle of beer to empty out the remainder of the cool beverage into her mouth.  Warrick gave her a half roll of his eyes and shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Leave it to you to come up with an answer like that.”<br>
<br>
“What?  They have to get the stats somewhere, right?”<br>
<br>
Warrick glanced past her and let out a small sigh before lightly shaking his head again.<br>
<br>
“Uh oh,” Sara said.  “Not another one?” she asked pleadingly.<br>
<br>
“What’s that make?  Five or six?”<br>
<br>
Sara groaned and let her head flop forward.  A different man had come over to hit on her every ten to fifteen minutes since they had arrived at the small dive of a bar and Warrick had made a game out of it by guessing how many drinks it had taken for them to get up the intoxicated bravado to come and ask her out.  She watched as Warrick leaned back in his chair, carefully observing the man who had just risen from his seat and was slowly making his way over to their table.<br>
<br>
“He’s had at least four,” he said confidently.  <br>
<br>
“Great,” Sara responded with heavy sarcasm.  “You’d think they’d get the hint after watching every other shlup walk away alone.”<br>
<br>
“Shlup?”<br>
<br>
Sara winced.<br>
<br>
“I’ve been listening to Greg too much,” she said.  Warrick grinned and nodded slightly as an acceptance of what she said.<br>
<br>
“Here’s what I don’t get,” he said, leaning forward in his chair again, “they seem to be disregarding the fact that I’m sitting here with you.”  Sara let out a half snort followed by a bright smile.<br>
<br>
“Upset that you’re not the one getting attention?” <br>
<br>
“Funny,” he said with a purse of his lips and a small glare.  “And no.  What I meant was that you’d think seeing another guy at the table would ward them off.”<br>
<br>
“I guess,” she said.  “But you’re not exactly ---”<br>
<br>
“What?” Warrick asked pointedly, the grin on his lips betraying his tone of voice.  “Just because I don’t have the Grissom glare down doesn’t mean that I can’t look imposing.”  Sara smiled again at her friend’s reference, knowing the look Warrick was talking about only too well.<br>
<br>
“Hey sugar,” a slurred male voice said from the side of the table.  “What’s a pretty little ---” the man trailed off when he noticed the look on Warrick’s face.  Sara followed his eyes and had to slap her hand over her mouth as her body shook with silent laughter at Warrick’s almost perfect impression of Grissom’s annoyed and threatening glare.  The drunken stranger cleared his throat and stumbled backward a couple of steps.  “Right.  Hey – sorry man.  I didn’t know she was taken.”<br>
<br>
Sara and Warrick watched him walk away and then a burst of loud laughter erupted from Sara’s throat.  Warrick smiled amicably and then took the last swig of his beer.  Sara shook her head, trying to get her laughter to lessen.<br>
<br>
“I’d say you have it down pretty well,” she said.  “How long have you been practicing that?”<br>
<br>
“Oh no,” Warrick said.  “I tell you, you tell Gris, and I’m in deep shit.”<br>
<br>
“What makes you think I’ll tell Grissom?” she asked, her smile threatening to spread off her face.<br>
<br>
“Cuz’ you think you need to get back into his good graces.”<br>
<br>
Sara frowned and it only deepened when she realized that she didn’t have any beer left to quell the awkward silence that seemed inevitable.  <br>
<br>
“You know me too well for someone who barely knows me,” she grumbled, half-thinking that Warrick wouldn’t hear her over the bar’s background noise.<br>
<br>
“I know you better than you think,” he retorted.  They stared at each other, the rest of the world seemingly slipping away for a moment.  Warrick leaned over and tucked some stray hairs behind her ear.  It was innocent enough to be construed as a friendly gesture, but tactile enough to illicit a response either way.  “But not as well as I’d like to.”<br>
<br>
Sara opened her mouth in surprise, but quickly closed it, the corners of her lips curling upward into a smile as she arched an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Well enough to make this girls’ night out thing a regular event?”<br>
<br>
Warrick tilted his head to the side and grinned at her.<br>
<br>
“Only if you stop calling it a girls’ night out,” he said.  Sara chuckled and nodded, pushing the fallen hair back behind her ear again as it fell with her laugh.<br>
<br>
“I think I can handle that.”  Warrick’s grin grew into a half-smile and when he rose from his chair, he offered his hand out to Sara to help her stand up.  When she stood and he didn’t let go of her hand, she looked down to where their hands were joined.  He noticed her looking and interwove his fingers with hers, looking expectantly at her for a reaction.  She smiled and nodded before looking down for a second as they started to walk out of the bar.  ‘Yeah.  I think I can handle that.’<br>
<br>
